defaultCameraEntity.description: Entity with the scene's default, non-AR Camera.

arCameraEntity.description: Entity with a Camera component attached which is to be used for AR.

useLightEstimation.description: If set to true and available on device, use the LightEstimation API.

useHitTest.description: If set to true and available on device, use the HitTest API for placement of 3D objects on real-world geometry.

useInput.description: If set to true, listen to available device inputs for interacting with 3D scene objects (such as tapping on a phone).

enableOnDefault.description: If set to true, this Entity will be Enabled when not in AR mode.

updateIntensity.description: If true, the intesity of the Light component will be updated based on the estimated light intensity value.

updateColor.description: If true, the color of the Light component will be updated based on the estimated light color value.

updateRotation.description: If true, the rotation of the Entity will be updated based on the estimated light rotation.

maxIntensity.description: If updateIntensity is set, cap the light intesity to this value.

orbitSensitivity.title: Orbit Sensitivity
orbitSensitivity.description: How fast the camera moves around the orbit. Higher is faster

distanceSensitivity.title: Distance Sensitivity
distanceSensitivity.description: How fast the camera moves in and out. Higher is faster

distanceMax.title: Distance Max
distanceMax.description: Setting this at 0 will give an infinite distance limit

focusEntity.title: Focus Entity
focusEntity.description: Entity for the camera to focus on. If blank, then the camera will use the whole scene

frameOnStart.title: Frame on Start
frameOnStart.description: Frames the entity or scene at the start of the application."

inertiaFactor.title: Inertia Factor
inertiaFactor.description: Higher value means that the camera will continue moving after the user has stopped dragging. 0 is fully responsive.

autoRender.title: Auto Render
autoRender.description: Enable to render every frame. Disable to only render when camera is moving (saves power when the camera is still)

orbitSensitivity.title: Orbit Sensitivity
orbitSensitivity.description: How fast the camera moves around the orbit. Higher is faster

distanceSensitivity.title: Distance Sensitivity
distanceSensitivity.description: How fast the camera moves in and out. Higher is faster

defaultDistance.description: The default distance to position the target entity if hitTest is not available.

pointerPreviewEntity.description: (Optional) If set, an entity to be positioned on the current AR HitTest location.

useInput.description: If set to True, allow for input (mouse, touch) to scale this Entity.

scaleSensitivity.description: If useInput is set to True, how sensitive scaling is.

element.text: The human heart is one of the most vital organs in the human body. The human heart keeps on beating until the death of an individual.On average, our heartbeats seventy times per minute,which is close to forty-two hundred times per hour and pumps about 2,000 gallons of blood every day.

thresholdMode.title: Threshold Mode
thresholdMode.description: The thresholding mode to use. The standard ARToolKit options are available: Manual, Median,                   Otsu, Adaptive, Bracketing.

threshold.title: Threshold
threshold.description:
Sets the labeling threshhold value. The default value is 100.

The current threshold mode                   is not affected by the setting of this value. Typically, this property is used when the labeling                   threshold mode is 'Manual'.

The threshold value is not relevant if threshold mode is                   'Auto Adaptive'.

Background: The labeling threshold is the value which the AR library uses to                   differentiate between black and white portions of an ARToolKit marker. Since the actual brightness,                   contrast, and gamma of incoming images can vary signficantly between different cameras and lighting                   conditions, this value typically needs to be adjusted dynamically to a suitable midpoint between                   the observed values for black and white portions of the markers in the image.

videoTexture.title: Video Texture
videoTexture.description: Streams the camera feed to a video texture if enabled. Otherwise, a video DOM element is used.

cameraCalibration.title: Calibration File
cameraCalibration.description: Data file containing the calibration properties for the camera to be used

detectionMode.title: Detection Mode
detectionMode.description: The pattern detection determines the method by which ARToolKit matches detected squares                   in the video image to marker templates and/or IDs. ARToolKit can match against pictorial                   "template" markers, whose pattern files are created with the mk_patt utility, in either                   colour or mono, and additionally can match against 2D-barcode-type "matrix" markers, which                   have an embedded marker ID. Two different two-pass modes are also available, in which a                   matrix-detection pass is made first, followed by a template-matching pass. Defaults to                   "Color Template".

processingMode.title: Processing Mode
processingMode.description: When the image processing mode is "Frame", ARToolKit processes all pixels in each incoming                   image to locate markers. When the mode is "Field", ARToolKit processes pixels in only every                   second pixel row and column. This is useful both for handling images from interlaced video                   sources (where alternate lines are assembled from alternate fields and thus have one field                   time-difference, resulting in a "comb" effect) such as Digital Video cameras. The effective                   reduction by 75% in the pixels processed also has utility in accelerating tracking by                   effectively reducing the image size to one quarter size, at the cost of pose accuracy.

labelingMode.title: Labeling Mode
labelingMode.description:
Select between detection of black markers and white markers.

ARToolKit's labeling                   algorithm can work with both black-bordered markers on a white background ("Black Region")                   or white-bordered markers on a black background ("White Region"). This property allows                   you to specify the type of markers to look for. Note that this does not affect the                   pattern-detection algorithm which works on the interior of the marker.

trackAlternateFrames.title: Track Alternate Frames
trackAlternateFrames.description: If selected, tracking is only performed on every other update. This can increase lag in tracking but                   will reduce CPU load.

debugOverlay.title: Debug Overlay
debugOverlay.description: Enables or disables the debug overlay. When enabled, a black and white debug image is generated during                   marker detection. The debug image is useful for visualizing the binarization process and choosing a                   threshold value. The image is displayed as an overlay on top of the 3D scene.

trackerResolution.title: Tracker Resolution
trackerResolution.description: Controls the resolution of the tracker image. Each video frame is copied to the tracker image for                   marker detection. Reducing the tracker image resolution will speed up marker detection but will                   also make it less precise. For example, a video camera source may have a resolution of 640x480.                   The tracker image will have the following resolutions based on the selected option: 'Full': 640x480,                   'Three Quarters': 480x360, 'Half': 320x240, 'Quarter': 160x120.

matrixCodeType.title: Matrix Code Type
matrixCodeType.description:
Set the size and ECC algorithm to be used for matrix code (2D barcode) marker detection.

                   When matrix-code (2D barcode) marker detection is enabled (see Detection Mode)                   then the size of the barcode pattern and the type of error checking and correction (ECC)                   with which the markers were produced can be set via this function.

                   This setting is global to a given AR Camera; It is not possible to have two different matrix                   code types in use at once. Defaults to 3x3.

pattern.title: Pattern
pattern.description: The marker pattern to track. This can be the Hiro or Kanji markers or a marker you have generated yourself.

width.title: Width
width.description: The width of the marker. Defaults to 1.

deactivationTime.title: Deactivation Time
deactivationTime.description: The time in seconds from when a marker is lost before its children are deactivated. Defaults to 0.25.

shadow.title: Shadow
shadow.description: Enable this option to generate shadows in the plane of the marker that blend with the camera feed. Defaults to true.

shadowStrength.title: Shadow Strength
shadowStrength.description: Control the strength of the shadow. 1 is full strength and 0 is disabled. Defaults to 0.5.

matrixId.title: Matrix ID
matrixId.description: The matrix ID. If no pattern template is set, the marker is a matrix. Defaults to 0.

orbitSensitivity.title: Orbit Sensitivity
orbitSensitivity.description: How fast the camera moves around the orbit. Higher is faster
